article.headline: Gophers struggle on road again with loss to Badgers
article.linkText: Wisconsin keesp slim Big Ten lead by beating Gophers
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- With a loud, sellout crowd cheering on Minnesota as it cut into the lead, the Wisconsin Badgers stayed calm and won by playing simple basketball. Kirk Penney and Alando Tucker each scored 16 points as Wisconsin held off the Gophers 69-61 on Sunday. After leading the entire game, the Badgers (21-6, 11-4 Big Ten) saw their 10-point halftime advantage slowly whittled away. But they never allowed Minnesota (16-9, 8-6) to keep the momentum, stopping each Gophers rally by matching them shot for shot. As the game wound down, Minnesota cut the lead to two points on several occasions. But the Badgers took advantage of Minnesota's foul troubles, went inside and stayed in front with free throws. "That was a very tough environment,'' Penney said of the 14,907 in attendance. "Fortunately, we got to the line and managed to pull it out.'' With the win, the Badgers maintained their slim lead in the Big Ten over Illinois, which beat Michigan on Saturday. Wisconsin, which won its third straight, ends the regular season against the Illini on Wednesday. But the Badgers said they kept their concentration against the Gophers because they weren't worrying about the conference standings. "Maintaining the lead in the Big Ten wasn't really on our mind,'' Badgers forward Mike Wilkinson said. "It was just getting the job done here.'' With Wisconsin leading 63-60 with 54.2 seconds remaining, Moe Hargrow went to the free-throw line but made only one of his two foul shots. Freddie Owens, who finished with 12 points, had his next jumper blocked, but he grabbed the ball out of the air and drained a shot from the free-throw line. "In the right place at the right time,'' Owens said. "I was fortunate enough that the shot went in.'' Rick Rickert missed a long jumper on Minnesota's next possession and the Badgers hit four more foul shots to close out the game. The loss was a blow to Minnesota's NCAA Tournament hopes. The Gophers are trying to avoid a second straight NIT appearance. The Gophers, who are 2-6 on the road this year, finish the regular season at Indiana and at Illinois. "Everybody's down, because we knew we had to win this game, now we have to win both games in a row,'' Minnesota's Jerry Holman said. "I'm not going to say our tournament hopes are down the drain, that's not true.'' Penney, who went 5-for-7 from the floor, scored all of his points on 3-pointers while Tucker went 5-for-6. Rickert led Minnesota with 22 points on 10-for-17 shooting, but only one other Minnesota player, Holman, scored in double figures. Holman finished with 10 points. The loss spoiled the final regular-season home game for Holman and fellow senior Kevin Burleson, who scored only five points and missed a crucial layup with 1:25 remaining. "We wanted to win so bad, it just hurt a lot not to be able to get it for the seniors,'' Michael Bauer said. "We just have to keep our heads up and stay together.'' Penney hit a 3-pointer at the 12:26 mark to give Wisconsin a 48-39 lead. But the Gophers got a three from Bauer, a layup from Jeff Hagen and a baseline jumper by Rickert to cut the lead to two points. They stayed with Wisconsin the rest of the way, but couldn't get any closer. "This was a huge game, it's really painful. It just hurts a lot,'' Rickert said. Wisconsin opened the game by hitting its first five shots while the Gophers struggled from the field. The Badgers took advantage of Minnesota's poor shooting and opened a 10-point lead midway through the first half. Minnesota was able to climb back into the game by using a zone defense in the second half. But the Gophers went only 1-for-5 from the foul line. "We found their soft spots,'' Wisconsin coach Bo Ryan said. "They do a good job on their home court. We saw a lot of tape of them taking a lot of teams out of games. Fortunately, we were able to overcome that.''
